Date: 14 Sep 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hindustani Times [edited]
<http://www.hindustantimes.com/news/181_374404,000900040003.htm>

Leptospirosis claims 27 lives in Gujarat
----------------------------------------
At least 27 people in south Gujarat have lost their lives to leptospirosis,
a disease spread by rodents, in less than a week.
With the death of 2 farm laborers on Fri, 13 Sep 2003, the official toll
reached 27 for the last 4 days even as 25 new patients were admitted to the
Surat civil hospital. Officials said 177 victims of the disease from 131
villages are under treatment. The disease has spread in Surat, Navasari,
and Valsad districts. Unconfirmed reports put the toll higher and the
affected patients at over 500.
"We conducted tests on 127 suspected patients of whom 60 tested positive,"
said MK Wadhel, superintendent of Surat's new civil hospital.
"The disease is common during the monsoon. It is caused when barefoot
walkers come in contact with the urine of rats affected by the disease,"
Gujarat health secretary SK Nanda said. "There is no cause for alarm, as
this is a seasonal problem and is under control," he added.
Most of the patients are farmhands belonging to rural regions where people
usually walk barefoot. People with low immunity levels are more susceptible
to the disease, medical authorities said.
In order to cure it, the disease [generally - Mod.LL] needs to be detected
early, within the first 3 or 4 days. However, it can soon cause
irreversible damage to kidney and liver and prove fatal, medical
authorities pointed out.
Surat Medical College has initiated various steps to contain the outbreak
and send medicines to affected villages. "We have started an awareness
campaign in rural areas to make people aware of the causes of the disease.
We have supplied antibiotics to our centers in the affected regions," a
source at the medical college said.
